# Abstract

Wheat, the major staple crop of the world, is susceptible to many diseases and pests, causing significant yield losses. Timely and precise management of those diseases is therefore necessary to reduce loss and maintain food security. Though Unmanned Aerial Vehicles (UAVs) have emerged as a revolutionary technology to detect disease symptoms in crops, accurate detection and quantification are still challenging. Thus, this research is conducted to develop models that help in early disease detection in wheat crops using multispectral imagery. For data collection, the multispectral UAVs were flown periodically during the years 2023 and 2024 on wheat breeding trials at the OSU Agronomy Research Station, Stillwater. The flights were carried out at an altitude of 30m with a ground resolution of 1.5cm per pixel, and the ground control points (GCPs) were installed for precise georeferencing. Vegetation indices (VIs) from RGB, multispectral RGB, and multispectral sensors will be used, and their statistical summary will be calculated for spatial analysis. The VIs will also be filtered based on plant height thresholds. Principal Component Analysis (PCA) will be used as a feature reduction method, and thus derived PCs will be used as predictors to fit the models, whereas the disease ratings will be used as ground truth data. The trained model will be able to show comparable accuracy in disease scoring using UAVs than visual ratings. The developed model could be used to analyze other plant diseases in the future.

