# Methodology:

## Research Site

The research experiment will be conducted at the OSU Agronomy Research Station, located at Stillwater (36°07'19.8'' N, 97°05'31.5'' W). The flights will be conducted at an altitude of 30 meters above ground level (AGL) with a ground sampling distance (GSD) of 1.5 cm per pixel. A total of 12 ground control points (GCPs) will be installed for accurate georeferencing of the field. The nursery at Stillwater was Dual Purpose Observation Nursery (DPON) which had 1928 F4:6 experimental lines, managed by OSU wheat improvement team, that were planted in an augmented design and with a plot dimension of 1.3 m × 3.0 m

## UAV platform and datasets

The high-resolution multispectral images will be captured by a DJI Phantom 4 multispectral UAV, having six sensors, mounted on a stabilized gimbal. The sensors contain 5 multispectral narrow-band sensors that captures Red, Green, Blue, RedEdge, and NIR bands, respectively, and one RGB sensor. The data from the years 2023 and 2024 will be used for Study-I, whereas 2023-2026 year's data will be used for Study-II. Disease ratings of Barley Yellow Dwarf (BYD) will be used as ground truth data. The UAV flights will be in accordance with the dates when the BYD rating will be taken.

## Data Processing

**Study-I:**

There will be a total of three factors for analysis, namely: vegetation indices (VIs), statistical descriptors, and height levels. So, a 2\*4\*2 experimental design will be used; with two bands, four statistics, and two height levels.

To identify which vegetation indices have the highest predicting ability for BYD disease, VIs derived from RGB, multispectral RGB, and multispectral bands—three from each—will be used. The VIs from the RGB bands include VARI, RGBVI, and GRVI, whereas the multispectral bands include NDVI, GNDVI, and NDRE. The multispectral-RGB bands VIs will be similar to that of RGB bands, as only the sensors are different, while the band names are not. The combination of field-plot-level statistical descriptors will be used; with four levels namely- Mean, Mean\*variance, Mean\*variance\*skewness, and Mean\*variance\*skewness\*kurtosis.

Normalized Difference Vegetation Index (NDVI), being the most commonly used VI, was used to distinguish vegetation pixels from the background pixels in the research done by [@hao2025] to detect yellow dwarf disease in wheat. Similarly, NDVI provided higher statistical dependency, as both NIR and Red bands used in NDVI calculation are sensitive to Yellow Rust disease [@su2019]. Contrast, correlation, homogeneity, energy, entropy, root mean square, skewness, kurtosis, variance, smoothness, etc. are some of the textural features used for plant disease detection [@javidan2024].

The use of digital elevation models (DEMs) for segregating the pixels with flag leaves on them, as BYD disease is subject to infect flag leaves mostly, could be a new approach that will be used in this research. Height thresholds based on average plot plant height are generated at first from DEM, and later used to subset pixels with height above the thresholds. Two different height thresholds will be considered: full canopy and 90th percentile canopy.

Plants were rated by counting the number of infected flag leaves as they show the distinct symptoms of BYD, characterized by small reddish to pinkish coloration on leaf tips [@perkins2018]. To assess the infection of YD virus in wheat, plants were visually rated by observing the symptoms present on the flag leaves, with no distinguishable symptoms as a 0 rating to a flag leaf completely discolored and curled as a 5 [@bowen2003].

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) will be used to separate several correlated predictors and segregate a new set of eigenvectors to be used as predictors, as related components might bring errors during the model development and prediction. PCA explains most of the data with minimal loss of information by reducing high dimensional data to a few principal components [@zhang2020]. [@wang2012] used PCA for reducing dimensions in data processing for the image recognition of wheat stripe rust, wheat leaf rust, grape downy mildew, and grape powdery mildew.

The set of new principal components, generated from PCA, will then be used as predictors in a Linear regression model, whereas the BYD ratings will be used as ground truth data. The model performance will be analyzed by calculating accuracy, precision, macro-precision, and recall.

From the first study, we will get a sets of features that best predicts BYD severity, and those features will then be used to fit different models in second study.

**Study-II:**

Out of several features generated as the outcome of first study, the top one-third outstanding features will be used as predictors to compare different models for BYD disease prediction.

The comparison between linear regression, random forest, support vector machines, and deep learning models will be carried out as the main objective of the second study. The models will be compared based on predictive performance, computational efficiency and interpretability to predict the disease.

[@su2018]used random forest as the classifier using 18 spectral VI as predictors to generate yellow rust disease severity map. [@nema2018] used support vector machines for wheat leaf disease detection where results showed the diseased and un-diseased leaf from the test sets. Similarly, [@wang2011] showed that support vector machine achieved higher fitting accuracy and prediction accuracy while predicting wheat stripe rust.

